  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="sec-eyebrow">What HIPEC is and why it matters</div>
    <h2 class="sec-h"><span class="te-content">HIPEC అంటే <em>ఏమిటి</em></span><span class="en-content">What <em>HIPEC</em> is</span></h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <div class="te-block">
        <p>HIPEC (Hyperthermic Intraperitoneal Chemotherapy) peritoneal surface malignancy కి advanced surgical treatment. Process: first cytoreductive surgery (CRS) తో abdomen లో visible tumour deposits అన్నీ remove చేస్తాను. తరువాత heated chemotherapy (42°C) abdomen లోపల 60-90 minutes circulate చేస్తాను. Microscopic residual cells eliminate చేయడం goal.</p>
        <p>ఈ technique Sugarbaker (Washington DC) మరియు Glehen (Lyon, France) groups develop చేశారు. Initially "terminal" అని consider చేసిన peritoneal cancers లో, CRS+HIPEC long-term disease control, selected cases లో potential cure achieve చేయగలదు అని established అయింది.</p>
        <p>నా Hannover ESSO Fellowship specifically peritoneal surface malignancy కోసం. Prof. Beate Rau గారి దగ్గర PCI (Peritoneal Carcinomatosis Index) scoring, patient selection, procedure execution, post-op management అన్నీ specifically నేర్చుకున్నాను. ఈ training India లో rare.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="en-block">
        <p>HIPEC (Hyperthermic Intraperitoneal Chemotherapy) is an advanced surgical treatment for peritoneal surface malignancy. The process: first I perform cytoreductive surgery (CRS) to remove all visible tumour deposits from the abdomen. Then heated chemotherapy (42°C) is circulated inside the abdomen for 60-90 minutes to eliminate microscopic residual cells.</p>
        <p>This technique was developed by the Sugarbaker group (Washington DC) and Glehen group (Lyon, France). Cancers previously considered terminal have shown that CRS+HIPEC can achieve long-term disease control and potential cure in selected cases.</p>
        <p>My Hannover ESSO Fellowship was specifically for peritoneal surface malignancy. Under Prof. Beate Rau, I learned PCI scoring, patient selection, procedure execution and post-op management for these cases specifically. This training is rare in India.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
